SIMPLE: appropriation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Appropriation
<hw>Ap*pro`pri*a"tion</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>appropriatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>appropriation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of setting apart or assigning to a particular
use or person, or of taking to one's self, in exclusion of all others;
application to a special use or purpose, as of a piece of ground for a
park, or of money to carry out some object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything, especially money, thus set
apart.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Commons watched carefully over the
<qex>appropriation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The severing or
sequestering of a benefice to the perpetual use of a spiritual
corporation. <xex>Blackstone</xex>.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The
application of payment of money by a debtor to his creditor, to one of
several debts which are due from the former to the latter.</def>
<rj><au>Chitty.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Appropriative</ent>⟦br⟧
